Array value assigned on declaration and behavior

2D	CHAR ARRAY
------------------
char *str[] = {"one", "two", "three", NULL};

Remember to add "NULL" as the last element, without " ".
This array declaration does not add "NULL" automatically, like in 1D char array.

ex: 
char *c = "Hello";
In this case the string is automatically terminated with a '\0';

2D INT ARRAY
---------------
int	*num = {1,2,3};

In this case you can't add a terminating character as the last element,
because 0 could be a value.

So, how do you get the array length, so you can loop until the end of array?

len = sizeof(num) / sizeof(num[0]);

But there is a caveat to this, if such an array was passed as an argument, 
without the length of the array as an additional argument, then the above
method of finding int array length using sizeof() would not work.
If an int array is passed as an argument, it must come with array length as
an additional argument.

